<h1 class="title">Measure for Measure</h1>
<p>
The title is an illusion to the sermon on the mount.
</p>


<ul class="org-ul">
<li>"Our doubts are traitors / And make us lose the good we oft might win / By fearing to attempt."</li>
</ul>

<p>
2.1: "Some rise by sin and some by virtue fall."
</p>

<p>
2.2: "Thieves for their robbery have authority / When judges steal themselves."
</p>


<p>
2.4: Say what you can, my false o'erweighs your true.
</p>


<p>
5 They say best men are molded out of faults, / And, for the most, become much more the bette
</p>

<p>
Thoughts are no subjects, / Intents but merely thoughts
</p>


<p>
Its a play about public choice:  systems humans build to measure and judge each other — law, religion, authority, merit, chastity — are all operated by human beings who are subject to the same appetites and failures they are trying to govern
</p>


<p>
Measure for measure turns out to be not a law of the universe but a human aspiration, imperfectly applied by imperfect hands, arriving at outcomes that satisfy no fully consistent principle.
</p>
